  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Burkina Faso: advancing ESC rights</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As one of the least developed countries of the world, Burkina Faso has numerous socio-economic rights violations and abuses. A group of national and international CSOs had already come together as a platform to deal with these challenges. It was agreed to build joint capacities to analyse the problems from a human rights perspective, and to prepare a joint parallel report for the Universal Periodic Review (UPR) of May 2018. This was done, with AINL support since 2016. The thinking, to build on the UPR outcomes was for the platform to develop an action plan to follow up the UPR conclusions, by feeding back those conclusions to the communities involved in the preparation of the parallel report, and mobilizing them to influence government actors to implement the conclusions and recommendations of the process. This action plan was never finalized due in part to the coordination difficulty previously mentioned. During 2019, AINL/HURICAP surveyed , through the aid of a questionnaire 9 platform members to understand the challenge and plot a way forward. Based on the survey, AINL/HURICAP proposed to all members to submit individual or joint project proposals that would give follow-up to the UPR recommendations. Out of these proposals, one gender-focused proposal was selected to be supported in 2020, which in the end did not happen as the partner could not meet our due diligence requirements.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the past few years, AINL supported a national network of civil society organisations working to advance the realisation of ESC rights (Plateforme DESC). After training and research, the network submitted a parallel report to the 2018 Universal Periodic Review (UPR). After the UPR session, the Platform encountered some coordination problems, which made further collaboration a challenge. In 2020,  the decision was taken to continue to work only with one Platform member on one specific issue raised at the UPR. Partly based on the Platform&apos;s lobbying, two states, including Denmark, recommended that Burkina Faso set up an alternative system for settling disputes relating to the inheritance rights of women. To this end, AINL/HURICAP envisaged supporting a project that focused on the protection and promotion of inheritance rights for widows. Yet, in the final stages of the project design, due diligence requirements could not be met by the partner and plans were discontinued.</narrative>
  </description>
